---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Container from '@/components/layout/Container.astro';

const description =
  'Level One Radiology is an independent emergency radiology publication written by Michael Hood, MD, an emergency radiologist at Mass General Brigham.';
---

<Layout title="About | Level One Radiology" description={description}>
  <section class="page">
    <Container width="reading">
      <header class="page-header">
        <p class="type-ui">About</p>
        <h1 class="page-header__title">About Level One</h1>
      </header>

      <div class="prose">
        <p class="lead">
          Level One Radiology is an independent publication about emergency radiology. It has one
          author, no institution, and no sponsor.
        </p>

        <p>
          I'm Michael Hood, an emergency radiologist at Mass General Brigham in Boston. I read the
          trauma and emergency imaging this site writes about. The content comes from that work: the
          findings that change management, the calls that are hard to make, and how the field is
          changing.
        </p>

        <h2>Why this exists</h2>
        <p>
          Radiology has journals for rigor and trade sites for speed, and not much in between. Journal
          teaching arrives a year late and reads like a textbook. Trade coverage is fast but thin. This
          site is for the middle: educational deep-dives, commentary while the topic still matters, and
          teaching cases you can use on your next shift.
        </p>

        <h2>What to expect</h2>
        <p>
          Articles are the product. Deep-dives explain the mechanism before the findings, so the signs
          are findable rather than just recognizable. Commentary takes a position. Cases support the
          teaching rather than standing alone. Articles run as long as the teaching requires and no
          longer.
        </p>

        <p>
          New articles go out by email about once a week.
          <a href="#subscribe">Subscribe at the bottom of this page</a> or use the
          <a href="/rss.xml">RSS feed</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </Container>
  </section>
</Layout>
